{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_idlewild_ver01/data/sn86076241/00271762318/1914010701/0019.xml":{"full_text":"The Carson City Daily fffipeal\nCARSON CITY, ORMSBY COUNTY, NEVADA\nKntered as Matter of the Second Class at the Postoffice at Carson\nCity, Nevada, under Act of Congress of March 3, 1879\nPUBLISHED EVEKY EVENING, EXCEPT SUNDAY, BY THE\nNEVADA PRINTING COMPANY\nT. D. Van Dtvort, Editor H. J. Coogan, Manager\nTERMS OP SUBSCRIPTION\nOne Year, in Advance, by Carrier $12.00\nOne Year, in Advance, by Mail $9.00\nThe average politician who announces that he hears the people\ncalling him is usually a pretty good ventriloquist. Columbia State.\noo\nGeneral Huerta, it i- reported, will move the capital southward\nto Iguala, though Patagonia would he much safer. Columbia State.\noo\nOFFICIAL COUN T OF STATE FUNDS\nState of Nevada, County of Ormsby, ss.\nTfon. Tasker L. Oddie and 11 on. George Brodigan being duly\nsworn, severally say they are members of the Board of Examiners of\nthe State of Nevada; that on the 31st day of December, 1913, they\n(after having ascertained from the books of the State Controller the\namount of money which should be in the treasury) made an official\nexamination and count of the money and vouchers for money in the\nState Treasury of Nevada, and found the same correct, as follows:\nCoin (total as per Controller) $525 138 71\nPaid coin vouchers not returned to Controller 236 683 77\nOffical Advertising Medium of the State of Nevada and for the\nCounty of Ormsby, Nevada\nThe Carson City Daily Appeal is the real live advertising medium\nof this section as is evidenced by its carrying a larger\namount of advertising than any paper in the city.\nJANUARY 7, 1914\nWEDNESDAY EVENING\nTHE TIME IS RIPE\nWith the passage of the tariff and currency bills and the coming\nof the new year it is a pleasure to note the tone of confidence that\ncomes from all part of the United States predicting all sorts of good\ntimes for the future years. Judging by the reports confidence, which\nafter all is the keynote to the whole situation, has been restored, and\nsimply means that the capitalistic classes, banks and like institutions\nhave more faith in the future of the country, more trust in the ability\nof the public to pay off obligations incurred and to be incurred, and\nare going to turn loose their hoards of wealth for legitimate enter\nprises and to responsible people.\nThe return of prosperity, which has been an absent member for\nseven or eight years, does not mean, however, that a plethora of\ncash is going to drop into the laps of those who are making no et\nforrt to help themselves or their communities, but it does mean that\nthose who are sincere and honest, who have a meritorious propositi n\nwill have no great trouble in raising the money to put it through.\nTo Nevada it means more perhaps than to any other state in the\nwest, for with the advent of the panie in 1907, many embryo enter\nprises, with more than a modicum of virtue, were wrecked to a de\ngree that knocked hope of the future plumb out of the projectors and\nleft theni almost on the shores of bankruptcy, but with the coming\nback of good times the tangled threads of their plans will be un\nknotted and with the aid that can be secured they will be revivified and\nmade to succeed.\nThis does not apply to any one industry in the state. Nevada has\nas great resources as any commonwealth in the world, but in most\ninstances they are in the immature stage. They want help to bring\nthem to the producing or prospering point and this they will receive\nif the effort is made, if the people will stand together, boost each\nother's project, quit hammering or knocking, and pull in the same\nchannel. The time is ripe for success, and the year 1914 should spell,\na new epoch for the upbuilding, the putting back on the raod of pros-,\nperity, of the state of Nevada.\noo\nWHY NOT \"FEMALE\"?\nNaval officers and their families at Washington are reported to\nhave taken umbrage at the phraseology of the invitations to Secre\ntary Daniel's New Year's reception. The ladies in particular are rep\nresented as \"not flattered\" by their designation as \"wives and other\nfemale relatives.\"\nThe secretary's offense seems to be that he has gone back to a\nmid-Victorian vocabulary for a word of excellent ancestary and irre\nproachable traditions, but nowadays not in polite use. But what is\nthere about \"femal'e' that should make it taboo in modern drawing\nrooms? Self-respecting women in Dr. Johnson's day were quite\ncontent to be called females. Authors once addressed themselves to\n\"female readers\"; and are the numerous \"female seminaries\" and \"fe\nmale institutes\" that used to flourish forgotten?\n\"Male and female created lie them,\" and mere man has remained\nsatisfied with the classification. Why should the \"female of the\nspecies\" resent it? Is such preciosity compatible with sex equality?\nDoes it accord with hiking and suffraKists bills of rights or the new\nfeminine freedom generally?\nThe south has remained more conservative in its speech than the\nnorth, and Secretary Daniels is to be commended for giving official\nsanction to \"female\" at this time when an overfastidious delicacy has\nwell-nigh driven it from the vocabulary of polite usage. Perhaps \"fe\nmale relatives\" is \"unladylike\" and not wholly \"genteel,\" but at least\nit is a perfectly good and proper English word.\noo\nWhen Woodrow Wilson was a candidate for the presidency some\nof his opponents assured us that as a professor of political economy\nhe was O. K., but as president of the United States he would be as\nclay in the hands of the political potters in Washington, D. C. Now\nthe chief complaint of his opponents is that President Wilson is the\ngreatest boss and ring master that ever run a political circus. That's\nwhat he was elected for, and if he can tie a knot in the tail of the\nElephant and Donkey and make them do team work we may give\nhim a second term. Better Farming.\noo\nIt is estimated that during the year 1913 over $302,(M X) was\ngiven away and distributed among churches, schools, colleges, orphan\nasylums, hospitals and for other purposes. The largest individual\ndonor was Benjamin Alttnan, a merchant of New York, who died a\nfew months ago. He willed $18,(X)0,00() to charity and for public in\nstifutions. Of the $3(X, 100,000 disbursed, over one-third was given by\nwomen philanthropists.\noo\nThe dispathes say that Paderewski, the great pianist, is guarded\nby three detectives to prevent dynamiters from blowing him up. He\nhas worked this press agent dodge now for the third time on arriv\ning in America and the Appeal suggests that he try something new.\nIt is not a bad way to get free advertising, but it is getting a trifle\nbewhiskered.\n-oo-\nCalifornia's population is being added to at the rate of 150,000 a\nyear. Must be something more than hot air in the attractions of the\nGolden state to draw such a multitude of new-comers. P.ut when a\nnew man decides to locate in California, he is not charged with be\ning a \"Johnnie come lately.\"\noo\nTo Carson merchants: If you want to increase your trade, ad\nvertise that you will meet prices of mail-order houses, and print prices\nto prove the truth of what you say.\noo\nHousehold hint An egg on the sideboard gives the diningroom\nthe appearance of cozy prosperity. More than one, however, might\nbe criticised as a vulgar display of wealth. -Toledo Blade.\n00\nWe trust those four Mexican deputies who voted against Huerta's\npolicies will find their cells comfortable. Columbia State\n$288,454.94\n$380,000.00\n300,000.00\n75.000.00\nCoin in trcasry\nSTATE SCHOOL FUND SECURITIES\nIrredeemable Nevada State School bond\nNevada five per cent bonds\nClark county bonds\nMassachusetts state 3 per cent bonds 797 000 HU\nMassachusetts state 3' per cent bonds 313000 00\nKlano state 4 per cent bonds\nCalifornia state highway 4 per cent bonds\nChurchill coun